technology.message: Facebook Image Classification and Labeling. A HTML Tag Exploration. Just a simple post on the power of image processing. A simple example is in our Facebook HTML code. Inspecting the HTML code (I didn't know why I did this), I found that they did a simple labelling of all the images on your Facebook profile, be it a thumbnail or a large image. They put the label of the image inside the tag of the HTML codes in an attribute called 'alt'. You can actually go through the codes by right click + show page source and do a simple ctrl+F (search) with a search string of "Image may contain:" and hit the search button. Then, you'll see which tag corresponds to which picture and you may analyze the description. Example 1, for my profile picture, I got: "Your Profile photo, Image may contain: one or more people, people standing, sky and outdoor" The thing is, everything that Facebook describe is actually correct. I mean at least for this photo. Hehe. Let's do a checklist: -One or more people: TRUE -People standing: TRUE -Sky: TRUE -Outdoor: TRUE Example 2, for me and my friends' picture, I got: "Image may contain: 3 people, people smiling, people standing and outdoor" Let's do a checklist: -3 people: TRUE -People standing: TRUE -Sky: TRUE -Outdoor: TRUE Cool right?! This is called Image recognition. Facebook, Google and other companies have been doing this thing for quite a while. That's how you automate the work of describing/labelling/classifying a picture using machine knowledge/learning. However, in some other images, Facebook unable to describe the image perfectly. This is normal in a machine learning environment. You just can't overfit! Example 3, my cover photo with the whole family: "Image may contain: 21 people, people smiling, people standing, child and indoor" Let's do a checklist: -21 people: FALSE. 23 in total incl baby. -People smiling: TRUE -People standing: TRUE -Child: TRUE -Indoor: TRUE The number of people is incorrect but "21 people" is quite good. I mean minus the baby and the little guy in green baju melayu and songkok because they blend in with the colours. It is acceptable. Anyways, don't get too excited about this. Maybe this is just a simple/mini labelling model and they got a bigger and better classification model at the back, classifying things and our behaviour without our prior knowledge? Who knows right? I mean, who cares about reading the terms & conditions when we signed up for Facebook, right? Hehehe :)

711319165616420.message: Facebook Image Classification and Labeling. A HTML Tag Exploration. Just a simple post on the power of image processing. A simple example is in our Facebook HTML code. Inspecting the HTML code (I didn't know why I did this), I found that they did a simple labelling of all the images on your Facebook profile, be it a thumbnail or a large image. They put the label of the image inside the tag of the HTML codes in an attribute called 'alt'. You can actually go through the codes by right click + show page source and do a simple ctrl+F (search) with a search string of "Image may contain:" and hit the search button. Then, you'll see which tag corresponds to which picture and you may analyze the description. Example 1, for my profile picture, I got: "Your Profile photo, Image may contain: one or more people, people standing, sky and outdoor" The thing is, everything that Facebook describe is actually correct. I mean at least for this photo. Hehe. Let's do a checklist: -One or more people: TRUE -People standing: TRUE -Sky: TRUE -Outdoor: TRUE Example 2, for me and my friends' picture, I got: "Image may contain: 3 people, people smiling, people standing and outdoor" Let's do a checklist: -3 people: TRUE -People standing: TRUE -Sky: TRUE -Outdoor: TRUE Cool right?! This is called Image recognition. Facebook, Google and other companies have been doing this thing for quite a while. That's how you automate the work of describing/labelling/classifying a picture using machine knowledge/learning. However, in some other images, Facebook unable to describe the image perfectly. This is normal in a machine learning environment. You just can't overfit! Example 3, my cover photo with the whole family: "Image may contain: 21 people, people smiling, people standing, child and indoor" Let's do a checklist: -21 people: FALSE. 23 in total incl baby. -People smiling: TRUE -People standing: TRUE -Child: TRUE -Indoor: TRUE The number of people is incorrect but "21 people" is quite good. I mean minus the baby and the little guy in green baju melayu and songkok because they blend in with the colours. It is acceptable. Anyways, don't get too excited about this. Maybe this is just a simple/mini labelling model and they got a bigger and better classification model at the back, classifying things and our behaviour without our prior knowledge? Who knows right? I mean, who cares about reading the terms & conditions when we signed up for Facebook, right? Hehehe :)
